  "prompt": "What is dyarchy and when was it introduced in India?",
  "response": "Dyarchy, also known as \"dual government\" or \"double government,\" was a system of governance introduced in British India under the Government of India Act of 1919, also known as the Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms. This system was implemented in the provinces of British India and became operational in 1921.\n\n### Key Features of Dyarchy:\n1. **Division of Subjects**: The subjects of administration were divided into two categories:\n   - **Reserved Subjects**: These were controlled by the Governor and his Executive Council, who were accountable to the British government. Key areas included law and order, finance, and revenue.\n   - **Transferred Subjects**: These were administered by Indian ministers who were responsible to the Legislative Council, which had a majority of elected members. These subjects typically included education, health, agriculture, and local self-government.\n\n2. **Dual Control**: The dual control mechanism meant that while some areas of governance were managed by elected Indian representatives, the more critical and sensitive areas remained under British control.\n\n3. **Purpose**: The introduction of dyarchy was aimed at gradually increasing Indian participation in the governance of their country, while still maintaining British control over key areas to safeguard imperial interests.\n\n### Implementation and Impact:\n- **Implementation**: Dyarchy was first introduced in the provinces in 1921 after the passage of the Government of India Act 1919. The Act also expanded the legislative councils and increased the number of elected members, although the franchise was still limited.\n  \n- **Impact**: While dyarchy was a step towards greater Indian participation in governance, it had several limitations. The division of subjects often led to inefficiencies and conflicts between the reserved and transferred departments. The ministers responsible for transferred subjects had limited power and resources, while the real control remained with the British-appointed governors.\n\n### Criticism:\n- **Limited Autonomy**: Indian leaders criticized dyarchy for not providing real autonomy, as the most critical areas of governance were still under British control.\n- **Inefficiency**: The system led to administrative inefficiencies due to the dual control mechanism.\n- **Discriminatory Franchise**: The electoral system was still highly restricted, with only a small percentage of the population being eligible to vote.\n\n### End of Dyarchy:\nDyarchy was eventually abolished with the introduction of the Government of India Act 1935, which replaced it with a system of provincial autonomy, granting more powers to Indian ministers and reducing the control of the British government in provincial matters.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
